---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Icon from '../components/Icon.astro';
import Divisibility from '../components/diagrams/Divisibility.astro';
import TwoExtremes from '../components/diagrams/TwoExtremes.astro';
import FirstCut from '../components/diagrams/FirstCut.astro';
import CutBringsWorld from '../components/diagrams/CutBringsWorld.astro';
import CenterNeverMet from '../components/diagrams/CenterNeverMet.astro';
import Circulation from '../components/diagrams/Circulation.astro';
import Nesting from '../components/diagrams/Nesting.astro';

// DRAFT front page — visual-led. Stood up at /pattern for review, unlinked from nav.
// Each beat of the ruled Section-2 spine is a visual panel: diagram + short headline
// + one supporting line. Full ruled prose preserved in the <details> "long version".
---

<BaseLayout title="The Pattern">
  <article class="max-w-2xl mx-auto" style="font-family: var(--font-body);">

    <!-- 1 · Hook + the one bet -->
    <header class="mb-14 text-center">
      <p class="text-lg themed-text-secondary mb-6">This began with a question I couldn't put down.</p>
      <p class="text-3xl md:text-4xl italic mb-8" style="color: var(--color-text); line-height: 1.3;">
        If reality is truly infinite,<br />how does that actually work?
      </p>
      <p class="themed-text-secondary max-w-md mx-auto" style="line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);">
        Not "really, really big." Genuinely infinite — no largest thing, no smallest, no edge, no
        bottom, in either direction.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="themed-surface border rounded-lg p-6 mb-16 text-center">
      <p class="themed-text-secondary" style="line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);">
        I can't prove reality is like that. So this is the <strong>one thing</strong> I'll ask you
        to grant — the only one. Grant it, and everything below is just logic. Refuse it, and we
        part ways here, no hard feelings.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- 2 · The logic falls out — visual panels -->

    <!-- premise -->
    <section class="beat">
      <Divisibility />
      <h2 class="beat-head">No smallest thing.</h2>
      <p class="beat-line">However far you zoom in, you can always divide again. The floor never arrives.</p>
    </section>

    <!-- distinction -->
    <section class="beat">
      <FirstCut />
      <h2 class="beat-head">To be anything is to differ.</h2>
      <p class="beat-line">A thing with nothing it <em>isn't</em> isn't there at all. To exist is to be a cut — this against not-this.</p>
    </section>

    <!-- two extremes impossible -->
    <section class="beat">
      <TwoExtremes />
      <h2 class="beat-head">So the two extremes can't exist.</h2>
      <p class="beat-line">Perfect nothing and perfect everything each have no difference left in them. Impossible — and infinity keeps you from ever reaching either end.</p>
    </section>

    <!-- distinction obtains (the turn) -->
    <section class="beat">
      <h2 class="beat-head">So there is always something rather than nothing.</h2>
      <p class="beat-line">Not switched on, not begun — its absence was never available. Distinction doesn't begin. It holds.</p>
    </section>

    <!-- a cut brings a world -->
    <section class="beat">
      <CutBringsWorld />
      <h2 class="beat-head">And a cut is never one-sided.</h2>
      <p class="beat-line">Two poles that define each other, a gradient between them, a center where they'd meet — one structure, arriving whole.</p>
    </section>

    <!-- center never met -->
    <section class="beat">
      <CenterNeverMet />
      <h2 class="beat-head">That center can't exist either.</h2>
      <p class="beat-line">It's the extreme where all difference cancels. So every structure circles a center it can approach forever and never reach.</p>
    </section>

    <!-- circulation -->
    <section class="beat">
      <Circulation />
      <h2 class="beat-head">So the only way to persist is to circle.</h2>
      <p class="beat-line">You can't rest there and can't pass through. Keep it in relation to you and keep moving. The circling <em>is</em> the stability.</p>
    </section>

    <!-- nesting / gauge -->
    <section class="beat">
      <Nesting />
      <h2 class="beat-head">And every center is a world of its own.</h2>
      <p class="beat-line">Inside every one is a finer one, with no end. No frame is the bottom or the top — wherever you look from, you're in the middle. The middle is everywhere.</p>
    </section>

    <!-- Landing -->
    <section class="my-16">
      <div class="themed-surface border rounded-lg p-6 mb-4">
        <p class="text-lg" style="color: var(--color-text); line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);">
          <strong>Stable things persist by circulating around a center that is never met</strong> —
          and every such center, seen from close in, is the origin of a finer world that can never
          hold still as a world of its own.
        </p>
      </div>
      <p class="themed-text-muted text-center">That's the whole pattern. The rest is just watching it turn up.</p>

      <details class="mt-6">
        <summary class="text-sm themed-text-muted cursor-pointer text-center" style="color: var(--color-accent);">Read the long version — the argument in full</summary>
        <div class="mt-6 space-y-5 themed-text-secondary text-left" style="line-height: var(--leading-prose);">
          <p>Start with something almost too simple to notice: for anything to <em>be</em> something, there has to be something it <em>isn't</em>. A thing with no edge, no difference, nothing it's not — that isn't a thing. It's not even there. To exist at all is to be distinguishable from something else.</p>
          <p>Now push the two together. A perfect <em>nothing</em> — everything divided away until nothing's left. And a perfect <em>everything</em> — all difference collapsed into one undivided whole. Both are states with no distinction left in them. And we just said no-distinction can't exist. So the extremes aren't rare, or far away. They're <em>impossible</em> — not places you haven't reached, but conditions that can't hold together. And infinity is exactly what keeps you from ever arriving at either.</p>
          <p>Here's the turn. Reality is <em>here</em> — you're reading this. It isn't the impossible extreme, and it isn't nothing. So distinction obtains. Not switched on, not begun — there's no "before" for it to begin from. Its absence is simply never available: absolute sameness can't cohere — not anywhere, not at any scale, not ever. It doesn't begin. It holds.</p>
          <p>And a distinction is never one-sided. <em>This</em> has no meaning without <em>not-this</em> — they hold each other up, each the measure of the other. That reciprocal relation <em>is</em> a gradient, with a place where the two stand equal, and a center where they would coincide and cancel. To have a difference at all is already to have the whole of it — two poles, a gradient, a balance, a center. One structure, read in parts.</p>
          <p>Now watch what that center is. It's where the two sides perfectly cancel — the very thing we just said can't exist. So the center of every structure is the one point it can never reach. Try to get there and it recedes, like compressing a spring toward its core: the coils crowd infinitely closer and the collapse never finishes. An asymptote, not a destination — the meeting never arrives.</p>
          <p>So you can't rest at the center — and you can't cross it either; there's no <em>there</em> to pass through. That rules out holding still and rules out going straight through. One option is left: go <em>around</em>. You don't have to <em>be</em> at the center to circle it. Around a center you can never reach, circling is the only form persistence can take.</p>
          <p>And there is exactly one place where the two sides stand in precisely the relation a finer world would need to hold together — and cannot hold it as a world of its own. Seen from close enough in, that locus simply <em>is</em> an origin, with its own two sides, its own gradient, its own center that is never met. Which has its own, in turn.</p>
          <p>Accept the one premise — no smallest scale — and the nesting never bottoms out. And no frame wears a number that means anything absolute: finer, coarser, first, last are only names for where you stand. Every frame, seen from inside itself, is a ground. No privileged rung, no view from any bottom — because inside is the only place there is to be. Wherever you look from, you're in the middle of it.</p>
        </div>
      </details>
    </section>

    <div class="themed-border border-t mb-16"></div>

    <!-- 3 · Recognition cascade -->
    <section class="mb-16">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-3 text-center">You've already seen it.</h2>
      <p class="themed-text-secondary mb-10 text-center max-w-md mx-auto" style="line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);">
        You don't have to trust the logic. Once you have the shape, it's hard to stop finding it.
      </p>
      <div class="grid grid-cols-2 gap-x-6 gap-y-10">
        <div class="text-center">
          <div class="w-14 h-14 mx-auto mb-3" style="color: var(--color-surface-nav);"><Icon name="wheel" size="100%" /></div>
          <p class="text-sm themed-text-secondary" style="line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);">Thirty spokes, one empty hub. Fill the hub and nothing turns.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="text-center">
          <div class="w-14 h-14 mx-auto mb-3" style="color: var(--color-deeper);"><Icon name="atom" size="100%" /></div>
          <p class="text-sm themed-text-secondary" style="line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);">Electrons never reach the nucleus and never escape it. They orbit.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="text-center">
          <div class="w-14 h-14 mx-auto mb-3" style="color: var(--color-lateral);"><Icon name="tree" size="100%" /></div>
          <p class="text-sm themed-text-secondary" style="line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);">A tree stands for centuries; the only living layer is the thin skin at its edge.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="text-center">
          <div class="w-14 h-14 mx-auto mb-3" style="color: var(--color-surface-nav);"><Icon name="valley" size="100%" /></div>
          <p class="text-sm themed-text-secondary" style="line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);">A valley is lowest, so everything flows to it. It gathers by giving way.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="themed-text-secondary mt-12 text-center max-w-lg mx-auto" style="line-height: var(--leading-prose);">
        Your own heart doesn't beat and then rest — the beating-and-resting <em>is</em> the heart.
        You are not a thing at a place. You're a pattern, circling.
      </p>
      <p class="themed-text-muted italic mt-6 text-center">The universe doesn't hold still. It circles centers it never reaches.</p>
    </section>

    <div class="themed-border border-t mb-16"></div>

    <!-- 5 · The reveal -->
    <section class="mb-16">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-6 text-center">And then, somewhere I didn't expect.</h2>
      <div class="space-y-6 themed-text-secondary" style="line-height: var(--leading-prose);">
        <p>
          I didn't go looking for this in an old book. I built the whole thing from that one
          question about infinity, followed the logic, and watched it turn up in wheels and atoms
          and heartbeats. And then I reread something I'd read decades ago and found dry — the Dao
          De Jing — and its opening didn't read like mystical hedging. It read like a coordinate
          system. Its recurring images — wheels, valleys, bellows, water — weren't decoration. They
          were the same demonstrations.
        </p>
        <p>
          I'll be honest about the direction of travel: I built the framework <em>through</em> that
          text, so its agreeing with me proves nothing — agreement with your own seed is exactly
          what you'd expect. It isn't evidence. It's the thing I'm translating. But watching a
          2,500-year-old page line up, character by character, with something you reached from pure
          logic is — whatever else it is — a strange and good feeling.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <div class="themed-border border-t mb-16"></div>

    <!-- 6 · The soft door -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <p class="themed-text-secondary mb-8 text-center max-w-lg mx-auto" style="line-height: var(--leading-prose);">
        I don't know if any of this is true. The whole thing hangs on one <em>if</em>. What I can
        do is show you exactly how hard I've tried to break it.
      </p>
      <div class="space-y-3">
        <a href="/confidence" class="block themed-surface border rounded-lg p-4 transition-colors hover:opacity-80">
          <p class="font-semibold">How solid is this?</p>
          <p class="text-sm themed-text-muted">Every claim with its status — what's derived, what's still open.</p>
        </a>
        <a href="/claims" class="block themed-surface border rounded-lg p-4 transition-colors hover:opacity-80">
          <p class="font-semibold">What it claims, and what it doesn't</p>
          <p class="text-sm themed-text-muted">The boundary — and the predictions that could kill it.</p>
        </a>
        <a href="/docs/rsm/rosetta-stone" class="block themed-surface border rounded-lg p-4 transition-colors hover:opacity-80">
          <p class="font-semibold">The vocabulary, and the discipline that keeps it honest</p>
          <p class="text-sm themed-text-muted">How the same shape gets read across domains — without overclaiming.</p>
        </a>
      </div>
      <p class="themed-text-muted italic mt-10 text-center">Pattern, not proof. Not sealed.</p>
    </section>

  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .beat {
    text-align: center;
    max-width: 30rem;
    margin: 0 auto 5.5rem;
  }
  .beat :global(.oir-diagram) {
    max-width: 210px;
    margin: 0 auto 1.75rem;
  }
  .beat-head {
    font-size: var(--text-2xl);
    font-weight: var(--weight-bold);
    line-height: var(--leading-tight);
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
    color: var(--color-text);
  }
  .beat-line {
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);
  }
</style>

<script>
  // One shared observer for every argument diagram: play once on scroll-in.
  // Respects prefers-reduced-motion. Hover replays are handled in each diagram's CSS.
  const rm = window.matchMedia('(prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)');
  if (!rm.matches && 'IntersectionObserver' in window) {
    const io = new IntersectionObserver(
      (entries) => {
        for (const e of entries) {
          if (e.isIntersecting) { e.target.classList.add('go'); io.unobserve(e.target); }
        }
      },
      { threshold: 0.45 }
    );
    document.querySelectorAll('svg.oir-diagram').forEach((el) => io.observe(el));
  }
</script>
